{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=1922 |Team=Kansas State Wildcats |Image= |Conference=Missouri Valley Conference |ShortConference=Missouri Valley Conference |Record= 5-1-2 |ConfRecord= 3-1-2 |HeadCoach=[[Charlie Bachman]] |StadiumArena=[[Memorial Stadium (Kansas State)|Memorial Stadium]] }} {{1922 Missouri Valley football standings}} The '''1922 Kansas State Agricultural College Wildcats football team''' represented [[Kansas State University|Kansas State Agricultural College]] in the [[college football]] [[1922 college football season|season of 1922.]] 1922 saw the Wildcats finish with a record of 5 wins, 1 loss and 2 ties, and a 3-1-2 record in [[Missouri Valley Conference]] play.
The [[Kansas State Wildcats football|team's]] head football coach was future [[College Football Hall of Fame|Hall-of-Famer]] [[Charlie Bachman]]. The Wildcats played their home games in brand new [[Memorial Stadium (Kansas State)|Memorial Stadium]], which opened that year. Before the season started, Coach Bachman arranged for a live [[bobcat|wildcat]] to be kept on the sidelines of the new stadium as team mascot. The wildcat was named "Touchdown," and the live mascot started a tradition that lasted over fifty years, until it was ended in the 1970s with the death of "Touchdown VIII."
At the conclusion of the season, [[Guard (American football)|guard]] Ray Hahn was named a first team All-American by [[Grantland Rice]], becoming the first football player in school history to be so honored.
